ations for the ability of elites to control land. Author Assan Sarr argues for a nuanced understanding of land and its historic value in Africa. Moving beyond a recognition of the material value of land, Sarr'sanalysis highlights its cultural and social worth, pointing out the spiritual associations the land generated and the ways that certain people gained privileged access to those spiritual powers. By emphasizing that the land aroundthe Gambia River both inspired and gave form to a cosmology of ritual and belief, the book points to what might be considered an indigenous tradition of ecological preservation and protection. Assan Sarr is assistant professor of history at Ohio University.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aIslamzGambia River WatershedxHistoryy19th century. 0aIslamzGambia River WatershedxHistoryy20th century. 0aLand usexPolitical aspectszGambia River Watershed. 4aAfrican Studies. 4aHistory of Religion. 4aModern History. 7aHISTORY / Africa / West.2bisacsh  aAfrican history.  aAfrican studies.  aanthropology.  acolonialism.  ageography.  aglobalization.  aindustrialism.  aislamization.  anineteenth century.  asociology.  atopography.  atwentieth century.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertBoydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package 2016z978311143131440uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978178204870140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781782048701423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781782048701/original  a978-3-11-143131-4  Boydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package 2016b2016  aGBV-deGruyter-alles